The Vice President of the United States, Mike Pence, announced the Papua New Guinea Electrification Partnership during a meeting with Prime Minister Peter O'Neill. The partnership aims to bring electricity to 70% of the people of Papua New Guinea by 2030. Pence praised the commitment of Prime Minister O'Neill and emphasized the United States' strong commitment to the region. He also highlighted the significance of this project as the first under the development cooperation agreement between the United States, Japan, and Australia. Pence expressed gratitude for the opportunity to partner with Papua New Guinea and emphasized the positive impact electricity will have on the country's economic growth and quality of life. He assured other allies and friends in the region that the United States will continue to work towards a brighter future in the Indo-Pacific.